Hypothesis:
Stealth driver loading techniques (non-standard paths/extensions, checksum-preserving signature tweaks, NtLoadDriver manual loads, BYOVD) can circumvent CrowdStrike behavioral rules and partial hash/signature blocks.

Part 2 shifts to the next problem: how do you actually get that driver loaded into the system without EDRs, antivirus, or Windows protections screaming alerts? That's what 'discreet' means here—stealthy integration so you can run malicious/vulnerable code at the deepest level without obvious traces.
First, normal driver loading is pretty loud:

You drop a .sys file usually in C:\Windows\System32\drivers.
Register it via the Service Control Manager (sc create/start, or an .inf installer).
It needs a valid Microsoft-trusted signature.
This triggers tons of telemetry: Sysmon Event ID 6 (ImageLoaded for drivers), process/service creation events, signature checks, etc.
Modern defenses like the Vulnerable Driver Blocklist, Driver Signature Enforcement, or HVCI (Memory Integrity) will often block or flag it.

Attackers want to bypass that noise. The article covers several evasion tricks:

Path and naming games — Put the driver in the expected System32\drivers folder so path-based rules don't flag it as weird. Or spoof the extension (load something named .exe as a driver, since the extension isn't strictly enforced).
Service type tricks — Avoid the obvious "type= kernel" when creating the service; sometimes use "type= filesys" or other variants to look less suspicious.
Signature manipulation for evasion — A cool technical bit: certain PE header fields like the Checksum or parts of the WIN_CERTIFICATE structure aren't included in the hash that Microsoft uses for signing validation. You can tweak those fields (e.g., with a hex editor or script) to change the file slightly—creating variants of the same vulnerable driver—without breaking the signature. This can dodge hash-based or simple signature rules in some EDRs. (Note: It won't fool Microsoft's Autentihash-based blocklist, though.)
Bring Your Own Vulnerable Driver (BYOVD) — The big popular tactic: Instead of writing your own unsigned evil driver, just load a legitimate (but vulnerable) signed one that's already trusted—even if it's old or has known issues. Exploit its flaws once loaded to do kernel-level damage.
Manual/low-level loading — Use APIs like NtLoadDriver directly (undocumented NT syscall) instead of sc.exe or standard loaders. This can sometimes be disguised as normal admin activity and avoids some SCM-related monitoring.

