Hypothesis: Mandatory User Profile abuse via NTUSER.MAN combined with Offline Registry API (Offreg.dll) hive manipulation can circumvent CrowdStrike behavioral detection by avoiding standard registry APIs, enabling persistent registry modifications that survive reboots without triggering monitored ETW or registry write telemetry.

Step 1 — Get a copy of the registry
The attacker grabs a snapshot of the current user registry. This is their raw material.
Step 2 — Edit it quietly
Using an obscure Windows tool (Offreg.dll) they edit the registry snapshot like a normal file — adding whatever malicious settings they want. No Windows APIs touched, so no alerts fire.
Step 3 — Drop the file
They save this modified registry snapshot as NTUSER.MAN in the user's folder. Just a simple file copy — nothing suspicious.
Step 4 — Windows does the rest
Next time the user logs in, Windows sees the .MAN file and loads it automatically. Windows itself applies all the attacker's changes — no malicious process running, no API calls, nothing to detect.
Step 5 — It sticks forever
Windows never overwrites .MAN files, so every single login loads the attacker's settings fresh. Permanent persistence with zero ongoing activity to detect.

